"""### **REPORT EVALUATION- STAGE 2 (DATA DISTRIBUTION)**
The second stage started with a full descriptive statistics summary of all numerical columns. The statistics revealed that the target variable is_fraud has a mean of approximately 0.10, confirming a severe 90-10 class imbalance before any preprocessing, and the transaction_amount column carries a minimum of just 10 rupees and a maximum of 18,673 rupees, which means the financial range across the dataset is extremely wide and skewed toward lower values.

The individual float column analysis confirmed this further when the ***transaction_amount returned a skewness of 0.563***, placing it in the moderately right-skewed category with a mesokurtic kurtosis of 2.516, meaning most transactions cluster in the low-to-mid range with a meaningful but not extreme tail of high-value outliers. The avg_transaction_amount by contrast returned an almost perfectly symmetric distribution with a skewness of 0.024 and a platykurtic kurtosis of -0.007, confirming that users' historical average spending behaviour is broadly uniform across the dataset and provides a clean baseline against which individual transaction anomalies can eventually be measured.

The categorical distribution analysis covered every binary and text column systematically. Foreign transactions accounted for only 6% of all activity, new device usage was 9.4%, and new location activity was 11.8%, all of which are low enough to be suspicious when they appear alongside a fraud label and important enough to track as behavioural signals. The transaction time histogram showed a broadly normal distribution of activity across the full January 2024 to January 2025 window with no extreme concentration in any single period. The failed logins distribution was heavily right-skewed, with approximately 70,000 users recording zero failed logins and the volume declining sharply at counts of 1, 2 and above, confirming that most accounts operate normally but a meaningful tail of accounts showed some login struggle behaviour.

Weekend transactions accounted for 27.9% of activity against 72.1% on weekdays. The txn_hour histogram was roughly uniform across all 24 hours, confirming that the platform sees consistent activity at every hour of the day rather than any dramatic concentration during business hours. The time_since_last_txn distribution showed a sharp spike near zero indicating rapid successive transactions, flattening into a broadly even distribution between 200 and 1,400 hours before tailing off, which is consistent with both normal behaviour and burst-style fraudulent activity.

Among the text categorical columns, Kolkata led in total transaction volume at 17.4%, followed by Mumbai, Chennai, Bangalore and Delhi in close succession, with Hyderabad the lowest at 16.2%. Mobile dominated device usage at 62.8%, followed by Desktop at 21.0% and Tablet at 10.8%. UPI led transaction type at 30.0%, followed by NEFT at 20.0% and IMPS at 19.9%, with POS, ATM Withdrawal and RTGS each hovering between 9.9 and 10.2%. The fraud vs non-fraud distribution was visualised last, confirming the 90-10 split and laying the groundwork for the class imbalance discussion in preprocessing.

## **STAGE 3 -BIVARIATE AND MULTIVARIATE EXPLORATORY ANALYSIS**
"""

